	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>pragma</b> [ Wed Mar 29, 2006 1:18 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Horrible Revolution controller?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">In <a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?p=11307#11307" class="postlink">this post</a>, Bregalad called the Nintendo Revolution console's airmouse controller "horrible". Does any other video game console have a mouse-equivalent pointing device that is not horrible?</div><br /><br />Well, it's kind of a misnomer to call the new Rev controller an "airmouse" since it's likely able to detect movement on all three axes, and possibly rotation along those axes as well.  A mouse style mapping would only require two axes of movement and no rotation detection.<br /><br />I would think that latency would be the killer here, but I seriously doubt anything could have left the laboratory that had any perceivable delay.  At least it uses RF with stationary sensors to get the job done - think "power glove on steroids".  This is a huge difference from the Akklaim IR 'remote' controllers of days gone by; man those things were awful.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Does any PC or console allow for up to four distinct pointing devices, one per player?</div> 
<br />
<br />Not as such - I think Nintendo is going to clean up here.  Especially once  developers figure out that you can have one of these controllers *in each hand*.  
<br />
<br />I do know that multiple mice in Windows all affect the same cursor, almost like the mouse events all tumble into one master mouse event queue.  I'm sure you could hack something up under Linux to maintain multiple mouse cursors simultaneously (imagine four mice plugged into a USB hub), but to what end?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


