		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Even the PS3 controller looks horrible</div><br />The "boomerang" design will be replaced by November.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">directionnal arrows "fusionned together" like the NES</div><br />The four parts of the PlayStation D-pad are separated to work around a Nintendo patent, which may still be valid in one or more jurisdictions.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I got a new PC for not too expensive, and it runs all emulated games at full-speed and with decent graphics (turn on interpolation to get TV-like graphics).</div><br />Could you afford to get one PC to connect to a large screen to play games and one to connect to a smaller 72-96dpi screen to surf the web and edit code? Or do you carry it back and forth?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">pragma wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Well, it's kind of a misnomer to call the new Rev controller an "airmouse" since it's likely able to detect movement on all three axes, and possibly rotation along those axes as well. A mouse style mapping would only require two axes of movement and no rotation detection.</div><br />A mouse has three axes: north/south, east/west, wheel up/down. Some mice have an additional wheel left/right.<br /><br />EDIT: <a href="http://www.vrdepot.com/vrteclg.htm" class="postlink">This</a> is why I call it an "airmouse".<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">pragma wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I'm sure you could hack something up under Linux to maintain multiple mouse cursors simultaneously (imagine four mice plugged into a USB hub), but to what end?</div>
<br />Multiplayer clone of Duck Hunt or Time Crisis, perhaps? Given that light guns don't work on LCD or DLP or double-speed CRT TVs, and such TVs will become the norm over the next five years with the transition to HDTV...

		

		</td>
	</tr>
